    <cp:dcSection>
        <dcterms:type>physical object</dcterms:type>
        <dcterms:provenance>In 1678, Louis XIV commissioned the court jeweller to cut and create it. 
            On September 11, 1792, it was stolen and then recovered by John Francillon in London.
            It was reported to belong to Thomas Hope in England.
            American Simon Frankel bought it from Adolf Weil and was again sold to Salomon Habib before it belongs to Pierre Cartier.
            In 1911, it was sold to Evalyn Walsh McLean.
            In 1949, it was bought by Harry Winston and donated it to NMNH in 1958.
        </dcterms:provenance>
